<statement>
<p>Graph the parabola <m>\displaystyle{y}=-{6}{\left({x}-{1}\right)}^{{2}}-{1}</m></p>
<p>The vertex is <fillin characters="7" /> Â </p>
<image width="52%"  pi:generated="problems/images/db61bcb5bcf24b92a4036b88a0436dee.png" />


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left({1},-{1}\right)}</m></li><li><image width="52%"  pi:generated="problems/images/7a5a572f235260847ca661123d897a26.png" />
</li></ul></p><p>The form of a parabola is <m>\displaystyle{y}={a}{\left({x}-{h}\right)}^{{2}}+{k}</m>. Because this parabola is <m>\displaystyle{y}=-{6}{\left({x}-{1}\right)}^{{2}}-{1}</m>, which can be written <m>\displaystyle{y}=-{6}{\left({x}-{\left({1}\right)}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left(-{1}\right)}</m> we know the following.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{h}={1}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{k}=-{1}</m>. Thus the vertex is <m>\displaystyle{\left({1},-{1}\right)}</m>.</p>
<p>To graph the parabola we can use the vertex and another convenient point. One convenient point is at <m>\displaystyle{x}={1}+{1}={2}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-{6}{\left({2}-{\left({1}\right)}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left(-{1}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle=-{6}{\left({1}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left(-{1}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle=-{6}+{\left(-{1}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle=-{7}</m>.</p>
<p>We use <m>\displaystyle{\left({2},-{7}\right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
